classes.name: EquipmentProtectionType
classes.comment: This enumeration attribute identifies the type of equipment protection.

enumitems.name: M_FOR_N
enumitems.comment: "M_FOR_N", means that M pieces of equipment protect N pieces of equipment.

classes.name: EquipmentSwitchData
classes.comment: This data type identifies the current protection switch status of an Equipment Protection Group.

fields.name: equipmentProtectionType
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the type of equipment protection for which the switch has occurred.</br>The attribute can take on the following value:</br>- "M_FOR_N", means that M pieces of equipment protect N pieces of equipment.

fields.name: equipmentSwitchReason
fields.comment: This attribute contains the reason of the last switch.

fields.name: epgRef
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the Equipment Protection Group for which the protection switch status is being reported.

fields.name: protectedEquipmentRef
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the name of the protected equipment.</br>In case of an M:N equipment protection type, protectedEquipmentRef always identifies a worker Equipment object.

fields.name: switchToEquipmentRef
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the Equipment object that is working after the switch, or currently working if no protection switch is currently active.

classes.name: EquipmentSwitchReason
classes.comment: This enumeration reflects the reason why a switch occurred.

enumitems.name: EQUIPMENT_FAILURE
enumitems.comment: EQUIPMENT_FAILURE is used when an instance of equipment has failed.

enumitems.name: MANUAL
enumitems.comment: MANUAL indicates a switch that was requested by the operator and includes forced switches.

enumitems.name: NOT_APPLICABLE
enumitems.comment: NOT_APPLICABLE is used, if a more precise value is not available.

classes.name: ProtectionCommand
classes.comment: This data type identifies the protection switch commands. See ITU-T Recommendation G.841 for definitions.

classes.name: ProtectionGroup
classes.comment: This object class represents the information about a trail protection in a Managed Element.

fields.name: type
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the type of the Protection Group.

fields.name: protectionSchemeState
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the state in which the protection scheme is in. FORCED_OR_LOCKED_OUT indicates that the entire group is locked; partial locking is indicated by AUTOMATIC.</br>Individual locks can be reported through transmission parameters on the appropriate TPs.

fields.name: reversionMode
fields.comment: This attribute identifies whether the switch is revertive or not.</br>The default value depends on the protection group implementation

fields.name: layerRate
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the line rate of the TPs of the Protection Group.

fields.name: parameterList
fields.comment: This attribute identifies any protection group specific parameters. Non-applicable parameters and parameters for which the value is unknown to the target OS may be left out.</br>See attached SD1-29_PGPParameters supporting document for values and descriptions.

fields.name: apsProtocolType
fields.comment: This attribute defines the APS protocol on which the switching function is based on.</br></br>Possible values:</br>- "G.783" in case of K1/K2 based APS</br>- "Legacy" in case of proprietary APS protocol, as for radio equipment.</br></br>No default value

fields.name: ituArcStateAndStatusList
fields.comment: See supporting document SD1-8_encodingX731M3100.

fields.name: asapRef
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the assignment of an Alarm Severity Assignement Profile (ASAP) to the Protection Group.

fields.name: protectionRelatedTps
fields.comment: This attribute contains the list of PTPs that belong in the Protection Group. The list of PTPs is partially ordered. The protecting PTP always trails its worker PTPs. The East PTPs are always contiguous in the list, as well as West PTPs.</br></br>At least 2 values.

inheritsDescription: SID Models::Resource Domain::Resource ABE::LogicalResource ABE::LogicalResource
SID Models::Resource Domain::Resource ABE::Resource
SID Models::Common Business Entities Domain::Root Business Entities ABE::Entity
SID Models::Common Business Entities Domain::Root Business Entities ABE::RootEntity

classes.name: ProtectionGroupType
classes.comment: Note: The values "MSP_1_PLUS_1" and "MSP_1_FOR_N" are also used for trail protection.

classes.name: ProtectionType
classes.comment: Note: The value "MSP_APS" is also used for general trail protection.

classes.name: SwitchData
classes.comment: This data type identifies the current protection switch status of a Protection Group or an SNCP reliable CTP. See supporting document SD1-34_protectionSwitch.

fields.name: protectionType
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the type of the protection for which the switch has occurred.

fields.name: switchReason
fields.comment: This attribute contains the reason of the last switch. During a switch notification the switch reason is known. If it is not cached in the target OS for later retrieval, then a NOT_APPLICABLE value is assigned.

fields.name: layerRate
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the layer at which the switch has occurred. The Layer Rate can be used to filter the switch notification.

fields.name: pgRef
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the Protection Group in case of a trail protection switch. This is empty, if the protection type is SNCP.

fields.name: protectedTpRef
fields.comment: This attribute contains the name of the TP that is protected. The protected (worker) and protecting TPs are fixed in a revertive Protection Group, the worker can be active or not at any point in time. In a non-revertive Protection Group, there is no fixed worker / protecting distinction. The worker TP is indeed always the active TP; after a switch, the worker and protecting TPs exchange their roles.</br>- For an SNCP, this is always the reliable TP.</br>- For a retrieval of a 2F BLSR, each TP is protected, and two SwitchData instances are returned.</br>- For a retrieval of a 4FMSSPR, each worker TP is protected, and two SwitchData instances are returned.</br>- For a retrieval of a 1:N trail protection (e.g. MSP), each worker TP is protected, and N SwitchData instances are returned.</br>- For a retrieval of a revertive 1+1 trail protection (e.g. MSP), this is always the worker TP.</br>- For a retrieval of a non-revertive 1+1 trail protection (e.g. MSP) switch, this is the active TP.</br>- This TP is a CTP for SNCP and a PTP for trail protection schemes.

fields.name: switchToTpRef
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the TP which is being switched to and is the active source after the switch.</br>This TP is a CTP for SNCP and a PTP for trail protection schemes.

classes.name: SwitchReason
classes.comment: AUTOMATIC_SWITCH is used when the switch reason for the automatic switch is not known.

enumitems.name: AUTOMATIC_SWITCH
enumitems.comment: AUTOMATIC_SWITCH is used when the switch reason for the automatic switch is not known.

enumitems.name: MANUAL
enumitems.comment: MANUAL switch indicates that a manual operation caused this switch, including MANUAL, FORCED and LOCKOUT switches.

enumitems.name: NOT_APPLICABLE
enumitems.comment: NOT_APPLICABLE is used upon retrieval of switch data for non-revertive groups, if a more precise value is not available.

enumitems.name: RESTORED
enumitems.comment: RESTORED is used for revertive groups to indicate a return to the normal state.

enumitems.name: SIGNAL_MISMATCH
enumitems.comment: SIGNAL_MISMATCH is used in the case the signal is ok, but is identified as coming from an incorrect source: TRAIL_TRACE_IDENTIFIER_MISMATCH, Signal Label Mismatch, etc..

classes.name: ConnectionSetupType
classes.comment: Indicates to what degree the management system and other system in the network are in control of the setup and routing of the FRE.

enumitems.name: PC
enumitems.comment: "Permanent Circuit" essentially indicates that the management system is in control and that what the management system dictates will not be changed by any other component in the network.

enumitems.name: SC
enumitems.comment: "Switched Circuit" essentially indicates that the network is in control and that the management system is a slave to network control.

enumitems.name: SPC
enumitems.comment: "Semi-Permanent Circuit" where the management system can setup the FRE but the network will deal with the routing.

classes.name: DeploymentActivityState
classes.comment: Represents the degree of deployment activity.

enumitems.name: DEPLOYING
enumitems.comment: At least one activate deployment activity or modify deployment activity (that is intended to result in a deployed capability) related the resource is in progress and has not yet completed.

enumitems.name: INACTIVE
enumitems.comment: There is no deployment activity in progress related to the resource.

enumitems.name: UNDEPLOYING
enumitems.comment: At least one deactivate deployment activity or modify deployment activity (that is intended to result in no deployed capability)  related to the resource is in progress and has not yet completed.

classes.name: DeploymentState
classes.comment: Represents the degree of deployment of the parts of a resource in the network.

enumitems.name: COMPLETE
enumitems.comment: All parts of the resource have been completely deployed in the network.

enumitems.name: PARTIAL
enumitems.comment: Some but not all parts of the resource have been deployed into the network.

enumitems.name: PENDING
enumitems.comment: None of the parts of the resource have been deployed into the network. The resource is not real in the network.

classes.name: Direction
classes.comment: Represents the direction of flow in a TPE/LT with respect to the stack of layer protocols.

enumitems.name: BIDIRECTIONAL
enumitems.comment: Signal flow is both Client-Server and Server-Client.

enumitems.name: CLIENT_SERVER
enumitems.comment: Signal flows down the LT, e.g. traffic is taken from a number of low rate clients and multiplexed into a higher rate server.

enumitems.name: SERVER_CLIENT
enumitems.comment: Signal flows up the LT.

classes.name: EndPoint
classes.comment: Represents the exposed points of the FRE to which associations to TPEs can be made. In a traditional model the points could be or role A and Z or Hub and Spoke.

fields.name: tpeIdType
fields.comment: TheÂ typeÂ ofÂ theÂ referenceÂ toÂ theÂ TPEÂ (concreteÂ name,Â SNPPÂ id,Â TNA,Â ServiceÂ endÂ etc).Â Â IndicatesÂ howÂ toÂ interpretÂ _tpeIdRef.Â EffectivelyÂ providesÂ theÂ nameÂ ofÂ theÂ namespaceÂ forÂ _tpeIdRefÂ toÂ ensureÂ uniquenessÂ (inÂ casesÂ whereÂ nameÂ spaceÂ valuesÂ mayÂ overlap).

fields.name: tpeIdRef
fields.comment: TheÂ IDÂ ofÂ theÂ TPEÂ associatedÂ withÂ theÂ EndPoint.Â TheÂ EndPointÂ mayÂ haveÂ noÂ TPEÂ associatedÂ duringÂ transitionsÂ associatedÂ withÂ editsÂ ofÂ ForwardingÂ orÂ inÂ anyÂ otherÂ caseÂ whereÂ theÂ FREÂ canÂ legallyÂ beÂ partiallyÂ interconnected.

fields.name: endPointDirection
fields.comment: The direction of the EndPoint (ingress to the FRE, egress from the FRE or bidirectional). This enhances the FRE direction statement for complex FREs.

fields.name: tpeAttachment
fields.comment: Where in the LT of the TPE the FRE EndPoint is attached (CP, TCP etc).

fields.name: endPointRoleList
fields.comment: TheÂ listÂ ofÂ roleÂ ofÂ theÂ endpointÂ ofÂ theÂ FREÂ inÂ theÂ contextÂ ofÂ theÂ internalsÂ ofÂ theÂ FREÂ structure.Â EachÂ elementÂ ofÂ theÂ listÂ hasÂ aÂ roleÂ nameÂ (e.g.Â TRAFFIC_FLOW)Â andÂ aÂ roleÂ valueÂ (A,Â Z,Â hub,Â spokeÂ etc).Â TheÂ listÂ mustÂ haveÂ atÂ leastÂ aÂ TRAFFIC_FLOWÂ entry.

fields.name: endPointId
fields.comment: ProvidesÂ theÂ IDÂ ofÂ theÂ EndPointÂ andÂ canÂ beÂ usedÂ toÂ identifyÂ roleÂ andÂ roleÂ groupÂ inÂ simpleÂ casesÂ whereÂ theÂ FREÂ specificationÂ allows.</br>InÂ someÂ casesÂ itÂ willÂ beÂ sufficientÂ aloneÂ andÂ willÂ removeÂ theÂ needÂ forÂ theÂ EndPointRoleÂ structure.

classes.name: EndpointDirection
classes.comment: Represents the direction of flow at the EndPoint with respect to the associated FRE and TPE.

enumitems.name: BIDIRECTIONAL
enumitems.comment: Signal flow is both into the FRE from the TPE and out from the FRE to the TPE.

enumitems.name: EGRESS
enumitems.comment: The signal only flows out from the FRE to the TPE.

enumitems.name: INGRESS
enumitems.comment: The signal flows in from the TPE to the FRE.

classes.name: EndpointRole
classes.comment: Extensible list of Roles that provide details of the visible abstraction of the internal structure of the encapsulation, i.e. that that can be seen and controlled via the FRE.

enumitems.name: ADMINISTRATIVE_MASTER
enumitems.comment: The point has a role of Master from an administrative perspective.

enumitems.name: FORWARDING_BRIDGE
enumitems.comment: The point supports the flow required for the bridging required between two INTERCONNECT FREs to form a ladder protection structure.

enumitems.name: FORWARDING_HUB
enumitems.comment: TheÂ commonÂ pointÂ inÂ aÂ HUB_SPOKEÂ FRE.Â TheÂ pointÂ canÂ feedÂ toÂ andÂ drawÂ fromÂ anyÂ otherÂ HUBsÂ andÂ anyÂ SPOKEs.

enumitems.name: FORWARDING_PROTECTING
enumitems.comment: A point that will be receiving traffic that is the same as traffic received by another point in the FRE so that it can be an alternative to that other point in forwarding traffic to a RESILIENT point in the FRE.

enumitems.name: FORWARDING_RESILIENT
enumitems.comment: The point can draw equivalent traffic from several other points in the FRE such that the alternative sources improve the reliability of output of the FRE at this (RESILIENT) point. This point appears in a PROTECTED FRE (which is equivalent to an ADD_DROP SNC).

enumitems.name: FORWARDING_SPOKE
enumitems.comment: The point can feed to and draw from any HUBs but not from any SPOKES in a HUB_SPOKE FRE.

enumitems.name: FORWARDING_SYMMETRIC
enumitems.comment: The point has an equal role to all other points in the FRE. There are no constraints on flow across the FRE so any SYMMETRIC point can have forwarding to/from any other SYMMETRIC point.

enumitems.name: REVERSION_MAIN
enumitems.comment: TheÂ pointÂ hasÂ aÂ roleÂ ofÂ "preferred"Â withÂ respectÂ toÂ aÂ protectionÂ switchÂ position.

enumitems.name: REVERSION_STANDBY
enumitems.comment: TheÂ pointÂ hasÂ aÂ roleÂ ofÂ "not preferred"Â withÂ respectÂ toÂ aÂ protectionÂ switchÂ position.

classes.name: EndPointRole
classes.comment: The focus of the role such as FORWARDING where the role described is related to information flow and protection.An EndPoint can have several role focuses but should always have a FORWARDING role (unless the simple endPointId in the EndPoint is used to summarise the role (in simple cases)).

fields.name: roleFocus
fields.comment: The focus of the role such as FORWARDING where the role described is related to information flow and protection.</br>An EndPoint can have several role focuses but should always have a FORWARDING role (unless the simple endPointId in the EndPoint is used to summarise the role (in simple cases)).

fields.name: roleFocusGroupAndInstance
fields.comment: TheÂ localÂ nameÂ ofÂ aÂ groupÂ ofÂ pointsÂ inÂ aÂ specificÂ structureÂ ofÂ interrelatedÂ rolesÂ andÂ theÂ instanceÂ ofÂ theÂ pointÂ inÂ thatÂ group.</br>ThisÂ isÂ essentiallyÂ directlyÂ equivalentÂ toÂ A1,Â Z1Â butÂ isÂ definedÂ toÂ allowÂ moreÂ appropriateÂ terms.</br>TheÂ groupÂ isÂ usedÂ whenÂ thereÂ areÂ multipleÂ repeatsÂ ofÂ theÂ sameÂ setÂ ofÂ pointsÂ suchÂ asÂ inÂ aÂ DOUBLE_PROTECTEDÂ FRE.

fields.name: rigorousRole
fields.comment: Name of the role in the context of the specification of the FRE type.

fields.name: softRole
fields.comment: AnÂ localÂ nameÂ forÂ theÂ roleÂ thatÂ isÂ notÂ rigorouslyÂ defined in the FRE typeÂ butÂ isÂ appropriatelyÂ unique as per the definition of the FRE type.

fields.name: additionalRoleInfo
fields.comment: Where the role needs more information.

classes.name: EndpointRoleFocus
classes.comment: ExtensibleÂ listÂ ofÂ focusesÂ ofÂ EndPointÂ role.

enumitems.name: ADMINISTRATIVE_ORIENTATION
enumitems.comment: Role simply provides administrative orientation information. This focus uses soft roles.

enumitems.name: FORWARDING
enumitems.comment: The role covers endpoint significant forwarding constraints (including protection). This focus uses rigorous roles.

enumitems.name: REVERSION
enumitems.comment: The role covers restoration constraints. This focus uses rigorous roles.

classes.name: ForwardingRelationshipEncapsulation
classes.comment: The ForwardingRelationshipEncapsulation (FRE) is bounded by two or more endpoints each of which may be associated with a TPEs. The FRE represents the enabled constrained potential for forwarding of information between those endpoints (i.e. to/from the associated TPEs) for a particular layer protocol (where the TPE must clearly have LayerTerminations (LTs) associated that operate with that layer protocol). Note that where the TPE is associated indirectly with a TopologicalLink (TL) the information from the FRE will be passed across the network via that TL and where the LT of the TPE is a layer protocol termination the information from the FRE will be prepared to transition layers of the network.Each endpoint of the FRE has a specific role in the context of the FRE where the possible roles and the interpretation of the roles are goverened by the type of FRE. The types of FRE are equivalent to the types of SNC described in MTOSI SD1-36 (refer to SD1-36_SNCTypes for explanation of SNC Properties, SNC Parameters, unidirectional SNCs, Point-to-Multipoint SNC, Routing Constraints and Route Discovery).An FRE may encompass a sequence of supporting FREs (which describe in more detail the route of the information comveyed by the FRE thorugh the network). The relationship is recursive such that a supporting FREs may itself be supported FREs (i.e. FREs supporting FREs supporting FREs). The FRE at the highest level of a recursion is referred to as top-level FRE. Note that a Call may have one or more parallel top-level Connection(s).An FRE may be used to represent various planning states. In these planning states the FRE may have only partial values for associated TPE name etc.

fields.name: deploymentState
fields.comment: This attribute represents the state of provisioning of the forwarding relationship between the set of end points.</br>PARTIAL: Indicates that only part of the FRE has been activated in the network.</br>PENDING: Indicates that none of the FRE resources have been deployed.</br>COMPLETE: Indicates the FRE has been successfully deployed in all Network Elements and no further intervention is required.</br></br>Note that a COMPLETE FRE is not necessarily enabled to carry traffic or carrying traffic.

fields.name: ituArcStateAndStatusList
fields.comment: See R_TMF518_NRB_I_0001 and R_TMF518_NRB_I_0004. </br>See supporting document SD1-8_encodingX731M3100...\..\Framework\SD\SD1-8_encodingX731M3100.pdf

fields.name: isFixed
fields.comment: This attribute identifies whether the FRE can be deleted via the interface (isFixed = FALSE) or cannot be deleted (isFixed = TRUE). </br>Where isFixed = TRUE attempts to delete the FRE by the OS will be rejected.</br></br>Where an FRE has a route (i.e. is known to traverse multiple NEs) all NFREs of the FRE must be fxed for the FRE to be fixed.</br>

fields.name: isAlarmReporting
fields.comment: This attribute identifies whether alarm reporting for this FRE is administratively enabled or disabled. </br>True = alarm reporting is enabled; False = alarm reporting is disabled.

fields.name: freType
fields.comment: This attribute provides the name of the type of the FRE.</br>The type is an expression of the traffic flow and potential for flow (accounting for protection switching constructs etc) through the FRE between the EndPoints of the FRE.</br>This attribute essentially provides the name of the spec for the FRE. The FRE may have further specification details provided via other specification mechanisms.

fields.name: direction
fields.comment: This attribute represents the directionality of the FRE.

fields.name: wasRoutedByNetwork
fields.comment: This attribute indicates if the current route of the FRE was computed by the managed system (i.e. "the network", all capabilities below the interface that defines the perspectiveof managed system) or not (e.g. the route was provided over an interface by a client EMS). </br></br>If rerouting is allowed, this attribute identifies whether the routing was carried out by "the network" or not.</br></br>If there is no network routing capability the attribute should be set to False.

fields.name: supportingFreRefList
fields.comment: https://www1.gotomeeting.com/join/149318416

fields.name: asapRef
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the assignment of an Alarm Severity Assignment Profile (ASAP) to the FRE.

fields.name: freProtectionPackage
fields.comment: Pulls in the package of attributes that relate to internal resilience of the FRE.

fields.name: freConnectionlessPackage
fields.comment: Pulls in to package of attributes that relate to preservation of information flow identifiers and other flow control properties across the FRE.

fields.name: freControlPlanePackage
fields.comment: Pulls in the package of attributes that relate to delegated routing capability utilised during the construction and maintenance of the FRE such as that associated with a traditional control plane.

fields.name: deploymentActivityState
fields.comment: This attribute represents the activity state of the current deployment request (e.g. activate, modify, and deactivate). If there is no in-progress deployment request, then the activity state is INACTIVE.

fields.name: endPointList
fields.comment: AÂ pointerÂ toÂ the list ofÂ EndPointsÂ andÂ henceÂ indirectlyÂ toÂ theÂ TPE.Â TheÂ FreTypeÂ isÂ definedÂ withÂ 2Â orÂ moreÂ EndPoints.

fields.name: transmissionParameterList
fields.comment: A list of specific parameters related to the layer of the FRE.

fields.name: layerProtocolName
fields.comment: Provides the name and potentially additional information such as version number for the protocol/layer that the FRE supports. Syntax and semantic to be specified.</br></br>Note: allowed value examples: â€œX2â€, â€œLR Optical Channelâ€.

fields.name: routeRefList
fields.comment: Identifier of the routes(s) supporting an FRE.

fields.name: nfdRef
fields.comment: Where naming does not relate the FRE to the NFD this association is used. Identifies the NFD that the FRE is within. Applies where NFDs are defined for or within ManagedElements.

inheritsDescription: SID Models::Resource Domain::Resource ABE::LogicalResource ABE::LogicalResource
SID Models::Resource Domain::Resource ABE::Resource
SID Models::Common Business Entities Domain::Root Business Entities ABE::Entity
SID Models::Common Business Entities Domain::Root Business Entities ABE::RootEntity

classes.name: FreConnectionless
classes.comment: Package of attributes that relate to preservation of information flow identifiers and other flow control properties across the FRE.

fields.name: flowIdentifier
fields.comment: This parameter contains the internal identifier of the flow through TPEs and decomposed FREs.</br>An example of a flow identifier is the IVID which defines the value to be used for VID in S-TAGs pushed onto the frames at entry to the FD.</br>When the value of flowIdentifier on an FRE is not â€œnull", the value of the  corresponding flowIdentifier for all of the TPEs attached to this FRE and to any supporting FREs have the same value as the as the flowIdentifier on the FRE.</br>If the FRE is performing flowIdentifier swapping inside (as opposed to only at the edges), the flowIdentifier on the FRE is not meaningful (and set to â€œnullâ€).</br>Note:</br>Since the flowIdentifier a TPE of the FRE has the same value as the flowIdentifer of the FRE (when the flowIdentifier of the FRE is not â€œnullâ€) any attempt to set a different value for the flowIdentifier of the TPE will be rejected.

fields.name: isEdgeFlowIdentifierPreserved
fields.comment: If True, the relevant flow identifier of particular information egressing the FRE at the boundary of the FRE is the same as the flowIdentifier used for that particular traffic at the ingress to the FRE. If flowIdentifier stacking or translation is applied within the FRE, the stacking/translation tables on all endpoints of the FRE will be set such that the above condition is satisfied for any flow.

fields.name: isEdgePriorityPreserved
fields.comment: This attribute shall indicate whether the egress Priority in the frame header must be the same as the ingress Priority

classes.name: FreControlPlane
classes.comment: Package of attributes that relate to delegated routing capability utilised during the construction and maintenance of the FRE such as that associated with a traditional control plane.

fields.name: routeGroupLabel
fields.comment: This attribute represents the Route Group the FRE is associated to. When a target OS creates a Call with diverse Route Groups, it assigns a Route Group label (which may be a number) to each FRE. FREs in the same Route Group will be assigned the same value for routeGroupLabel. FREs in different Route Groups will be assigned different values for routeGroupLabel.

fields.name: isUsingHomeRoute
fields.comment: This attribute indicates whether the Connection is currently using the home route or not.

fields.name: maximumCost
fields.comment: This attribute defines a number that indicates the maximum cost allowed for an FRE. The cost of an FRE is calculated based on the cost of the supporting links. This link cost represents a vector of one or more metrics, each of which indicates the relative desirability of a particular link over another during path selection.

fields.name: routingConstraintEffort
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the requested level of effort to meet the routing constraint when creating and when rerouting the FRE.

fields.name: connectionSetupType
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the setup type of the FRE. It indicates whether the FRE has been established by UNI signalling (SC) or NMS operation (SPC, PC).

fields.name: callId
fields.comment: Pointer to the "call" that this FRE is part of.

fields.name: connectionParameterProfileRef
fields.comment: Pointer to the ConnectionParameterProfile, an entity that defines a sequence of name value pairs that can be used to define class of service parameters and their values to be associated to an FRE.

classes.name: FreProtection
classes.comment: Package of attributes that relate to internal resilience of the FRE.

fields.name: priority
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the priority of the FRE. Allowed values are = "0" , "1" , "2" , ... where zero (0) is the highest priority.

fields.name: protectionEffort
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the degree to which  the level of protection specified in staticProtectionLevel needs to be met. The attribute appies during initial routing and rerouting.

fields.name: rerouteAllowed
fields.comment: This attribute specifies if the target system (e.g. OS, Control Plane, and ME) is allowed and/or required to reroute this FRE if there is a failure on this FRE, periodically to optimize the routes, or for any other reason. It is a target system implementation whether this is done using network routing protocols or if the target system detects the failure and takes appropriate action to attempt to fix the FRE. </br></br>The NO value means that the target system is not allowed to reroute the FRE. </br></br>The YES value means that the target system is allowed to reroute the FRE and is required to attempt to reroute it upon failure. </br></br>The NOT_APPLICABLE value is used when the requesting OS does not want to specify the exact target system behaviour. In this case it is left up to the target system to decide whether rerouting will be provided. It is also used if the target system is allowed to reroute the FRE but not required to attempt to reroute it upon failure.

fields.name: isRevertive
fields.comment: An FRE that is resilient may have a preferred route (intended route or home route). </br></br>In the case where the FRE is "revertive" (True) if the FRE is using an alternative route to the preferred route and the prefered route is not locked the restoration process will revert to the prefered route (from the alternative) once there are no relevant problems detected on the prefered route.

fields.name: internalResilience
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the degree of internal resilience/protection of the FRE.

classes.name: FreType
classes.comment: Extensible list of FreTypes that provide details of the visible abstraction of the internal structure of the encapsulation, i.e. that that can be seen and controlled via the FRE.

enumitems.name: DOUBLE_INTERCONNECT
enumitems.comment: The FRE has four points and is equivalent an INTERCONNECT for both A to Z and Z to A directions.

enumitems.name: DOUBLE_PROTECTED
enumitems.comment: The FRE has four EndPoints all of which are RESILIENT in two groups where each group has two members. This is essentially the combination of two PROTECTED FREs.

enumitems.name: EXPLICIT
enumitems.comment: The FRE is described in terms of explicit flows.Note: It is expected that this option will be removed and replace with the extensibility option to add new freTypes and associated spec details.

enumitems.name: HUB_AND_SPOKE
enumitems.comment: The FRE has many EndPoints. Some points take a HUB role and some a SPOKE role. This is essentially the Point to Multi-point configuration.The Hubs forward to (and from) all other points (including HUBs).The SPOKES only forward to and from HUBs.

enumitems.name: INTERCONNECT
enumitems.comment: The FRE has three EndPoints, and is equivalent to a unidirectional ADD_DROP_A (two A EndPoints and one Z EndPoint) with signal flowing from A to Z but with the addition of a flow from A1 to A2 and a flow from Z1 to A1.

enumitems.name: MULTIPOINT
enumitems.comment: The FRE has many EndPoints and there are no forwarding restrictions. The point role is SYMMETRIC for all endpoints.

enumitems.name: OPEN_PROTECTED
enumitems.comment: The FRE has four EndPoints, two As and two Zs and is essentially the combination of an ADD_DROP_A and and ADD_DROP_Z but only the A1 and Z1 are protected, A2 and Z2 only derived signal from Z1 and A1 respectively.

enumitems.name: POINT_TO_POINT
enumitems.comment: The FRE has two EndPoints only and forwarding takes place between them as dictated by directionality.

enumitems.name: PROTECTED
enumitems.comment: The FRE has three EndPoints where in one direction of forwarding two of the EndPoints (taking a PROTECTING role) make signal available to the third EndPoint (taking a RESILIENT role) so as to provide resilience and in the other direction the RESILEINT point provide signal to the two PROTECTING point).

classes.name: InternalResilienceLevel
classes.comment: This defines the degree of internal resilience/protection of the FRE.

enumitems.name: FULLY_RESILIENT
enumitems.comment: An FRE that will not fail if any single resource along its route fails (excluding the originating and terminating nodes for the FRE); for example, an FRE that is diversely routed.

enumitems.name: HIGHLY_RESILIENT
enumitems.comment: A higher level of resilient than is possible by simple diverse path routing. A highly resilient FRE should be able to experience several failures without affecting traffic. The alternative routes for the FRE have shared facilities and NEs other than potentially the originating and terminating NEs. Typically this is achieved using dual homing and ladder style network construction with a combination of both protection and restoration.

enumitems.name: PARTIALLY_RESILIENT
enumitems.comment: There is some resilience but the FRE route has at least one shared node and/or shared link at some point in the overall FRE path.

enumitems.name: PREEMTIBLE
enumitems.comment: May have resources taken to recover another FRE and hence may fail although no resources in the path chosen for the FRE have failed.

enumitems.name: UNRESILIENT
enumitems.comment: An FRE that will fail if any resources in its route fail.

classes.name: LayerProtocolParameters
classes.comment: Package of attributes that relate to a specified layerProtocol of an NFD.

fields.name: layerProtocolName
fields.comment: Provides the name and potentially additional information such as version number for the protocol/layer of thr NFD to which the transmission parameters in the package belong.

fields.name: transmissionParameterList
fields.comment: A list of specific parameters related to the layerProtiocol specified in the package that apply of the NFD.

classes.name: LayerTermination
classes.comment: The LayerTermination_ (LT) encapsulates the functions and points associated with one instance of a layer. The functions include the adapter functions, the termination functions and the connection points of that layer. In this case the term layer is essentially synonymous with the term protocol as use by other standards. All functions encapsulated have the same signal granularity, closely associated characteristic type and essential rate. A specific LayerTermination may be equipped with a subset of capabilities. Where the TPE is semi-transparent the layers encapsulated by a TPE are exposed by the LayerTermination_ set that it contains.The LayerTermination_ provides the relevant layer parameters for the semi-transparent TPE cases.The LayerTermination_ allows for detailed layer description of a TPE (potentially representing a port) and for precise association of the TPE with a TopologicalLink_ (or other representatives of forwarding relationship).

fields.name: layerProtocolNameList
fields.comment: Each instance provides the name and potentially additional information such as version number for the protocol(s)/layer(s) supported by the LT. Syntax and semantic to be specified.</br></br>Note: allowed value examples: â€œX2â€, â€œLR Optical Channelâ€.

fields.name: direction
fields.comment: This attribute represents the flow of traffic within the LT.

fields.name: ltType
fields.comment: TheÂ nameÂ ofÂ theÂ specificationÂ thatÂ describesÂ theÂ internalÂ constructionÂ ofÂ theÂ LT,Â indicatingÂ forÂ exampleÂ thatÂ itÂ possessesÂ aÂ G.805Â CPÂ butÂ noÂ G.805Â TCP (see MTNM/MTOSI SD1-18).

fields.name: index
fields.comment: Provides any relevant indexing of the LT (channel number, e.g. â€˜3â€™).

fields.name: networkAddressList
fields.comment: Pulls in the list of addresses relevant to the LT.

fields.name: forwardingState
fields.comment: Indicates whether The LT within a TPE is involved in forwarding traffic to/from LTs in other TPEs or not. This forwarding is described by the associated FREs and hence this attribute indicates whether there are any associated FREs or not.  In any particular case the values that this attribute may take are constrained by the value of the "direction" attribute of the LT. There is also a dependency on the value of the "terminationState" attribute of the LT.

fields.name: terminationState
fields.comment: The LT represents an encapsulation and aggregation of associated G.805 TCPs, G.805 Termination Functions and G.805 CPs. The terminationState attribute indicates and controls the configuration of signal flow within the LT indicating whether and how the signal is flowing between the G.805 TCP and the G.805 CP in the LT. There is a dependency on the value of the "forwardingState" attribute of the LT.

fields.name: transmissionParameterList
fields.comment: A list of specific parameters related to the LayerTermination.

fields.name: encapsulatedTmt
fields.comment: Pulls in the TrafficMappingTable related to the LT.

fields.name: thisLayerActive
fields.comment: Indicates that the LT is active in the stack of layers of the encapsulating TPE.

classes.name: LtForwardingState
classes.comment: Indicates the degree of forwarding, both in terms of capability and actually configuration, of the LT via the TPE into FREs in the NFD..

enumitems.name: FORWARDING_BIDIRECTIONAL
enumitems.comment: The LT is associated with one or more FRE in the NFD for both directions of flow.

enumitems.name: FORWARDING_FROM_LT_TO_FRE
enumitems.comment: The LT is associated with and FRE to allow signal to flow from the LT  to the FRE.

enumitems.name: FORWARDING_TO_LT__FROM_FRE
enumitems.comment: The LT is associated with and FRE to allow signal to flow from the FRE to the LT.

enumitems.name: LT_CANNOT_FORWARD
enumitems.comment: The LT is not capable of associating with an FRE.

enumitems.name: LT_FORWARDING_STATE_UNKNOWN
enumitems.comment: The association between the LT and FREs is unknown.

enumitems.name: LT_NOT_FORWARDING
enumitems.comment: Although the LT is capable of associating with an FRE it is not at this point.

classes.name: MultiRouteManagement
classes.comment: Where there are multiple routes available to the FRE this attribute package indicates the state of a particular Route.

fields.name: isIntendedRoute
fields.comment: This attribute indicates whether this route is the intended (prefered) route of the FRE (True) or not (False).

fields.name: includesResourcesUseByAnotherFre
fields.comment: This attribute indicates whether one (or more) of the component FREs of the route or TPEs  associated directly with an component FRE of the route is carrying traffic of another FRE, i.e. is involved in another route that is active, (True) or not (False).

classes.name: NetworkDirection
classes.comment: Indicates whether the entity supports forwarding in only one direction or both directions.

enumitems.name: BIDIRECTIONAL
enumitems.comment: Forwarding takes place in both directions.

enumitems.name: UNIDIRECTIONAL
enumitems.comment: Forwarding takes place in one direction.

classes.name: NetworkForwardingDomain
classes.comment: The NetworkForwardingDomain (NFD) object class represents the capacity to enable forwarding and potential for forwarding via ForwardingReleationshipEncapsulation (FRE) constructs. The NFD represents the capability to define a route for forwarding across the contained network. The NFD represents capability for one or more specific layerProtocols where the relevant boundaries for each layerProtocol coincide appropriatelyIt a grouping of zero or more:- TPEs which represent access to the NFD- subordinate NFDs which are a partition of its capacity (and hence completely contained)- TLs between the grouped subordinate NFDsThe TPEs associated may terminate TopologicalLinks (TLs). NFD instances and TL instances together define the network topology.New TPEs may be assigned to the NFD and TPEs may be unassigned from the NFD.Note that the NFD object may be used to represent routing domains or other administrative domains. The domain groupings may be orthogonal.The top level NFD corresponds to the whole network for the layerProtocols it includes.

fields.name: nfdRole
fields.comment: This attribute identifies purpose for the grouping provided by the NFD.</br></br>The NFD could be:</br>- ROUTING_AREA</br>- FORWARDING_AREA</br>- ADMINISTRATIVE_AREA</br>

fields.name: edgeTpeRefList
fields.comment: This attribute lists all of the TPEs that define the boundary of the NFD.

fields.name: nfdType
fields.comment: This attribute  provides the name of the type of the NFD. The type is an expression of the contained topology.

fields.name: supportingMeRef
fields.comment: This attribute provides the reference to an ME For cases where the NFD represents the capability of a single ME or a partition of the capability of an ME.

fields.name: layerProtocolNameList
fields.comment: Each entry provides the name and potentially additional information such as version number for (one of) the protocol(s)/layer(s) that the NFD supports. Syntax and semantic to be specified.

fields.name: ituArcStateAndStatusList
fields.comment: See R_TMF518_NRB_I_0001 and R_TMF518_NRB_I_0004. </br>See supporting document SD1-8_encodingX731M3100...\..\Framework\SD\SD1-8_encodingX731M3100.pdf

fields.name: nfdLevel
fields.comment: This attribute expresses the level  of the NFD in the hierarchy of NFDs

fields.name: nfdRoutingParameterPackage
fields.comment: Pulls in the package of attributes of the NFD that relate to routing.

fields.name: layerProtocolParameters
fields.comment: Pulls in the package of transmission parameters relating to a specified layerProticil of the NFD.

classes.name: NfdLevel
classes.comment: Identifies the level of a NetworkForwardingDomain (NFD)

enumitems.name: BOTTOM_LEVEL
enumitems.comment: There are no NFDs below this NFD. _supportingNfdRefList = NULL. _supportingNeRef is probably not NULL.

enumitems.name: INTERMEDIATE_LEVEL
enumitems.comment: This NFD is neither TOP_LEVEL or BOTTOM_LEVEL. The _superiorNfdRef and _supportingNfdRefList are both not NULL.

enumitems.name: SINGLE_LEVEL
enumitems.comment: There is no NFD hierarchy. Both _superiorNfdRef and _supportingNfdRefList are NULL.

enumitems.name: TOP_LEVEL
enumitems.comment: There are no NFDs above this NFD. _superiorNfdRef = NULL

classes.name: NfdRole
classes.comment: Identifies the purpose of an NetworkForwardingDomain (NFD)

enumitems.name: ADMINISTRATIVE_AREA
enumitems.comment: Defines some administrative boundary.

enumitems.name: FORWARDING_AREA
enumitems.comment: Defines the boundary for setup of forwarding.

enumitems.name: ROUTING_AREA
enumitems.comment: Defines a boundary for an underlying routing process.

classes.name: NfdType
classes.comment: Extensible list of identifier of types of NetworkForwardingDomains (NFD).

enumitems.name: CHAIN
enumitems.comment: NFD that encompasses capability from a simple chain of NEs.

enumitems.name: MESH
enumitems.comment: NFD that encompasses capability from a mesh of NEs.

enumitems.name: OPEN_PS_RING
enumitems.comment: NFD that encompasses capability from a chain of NEs that form part of a protection switched ring.

enumitems.name: OPEN_SHARED_PS_RING
enumitems.comment: NFD that encompasses capability from a chain of NEs that form part of a shared protection switched ring

enumitems.name: PS_RING
enumitems.comment: NFD that encompasses all relevant capability from a ring of NEs that operate in a protected fashion.

enumitems.name: SHARED_PS_RING
enumitems.comment: NFD that encompasses all relevant capability from a ring of NEs that operate in a shared protected fashion.

enumitems.name: SINGLETON
enumitems.comment: NFD that has only a single NE. Note an NE may participate in more that one NFD.

classes.name: ProtectionEffort
classes.comment: Indicates the degree of support of specified internal protection of the FRE that is required on initial routing and rerouting.

enumitems.name: SAME
enumitems.comment: The protection must be as specified.

enumitems.name: SAME_AS_OR_BETTER
enumitems.comment: The degree of protection must be at least as specified.

enumitems.name: SAME_AS_OR_WORSE
enumitems.comment: The degree of protection may be less than specified but must not be more.

enumitems.name: WHATEVER
enumitems.comment: The specified protection level is a preference but any other level is acceptable.

classes.name: RerouteAllowed
classes.comment: Indicates whether the network is allowed to reroute the FRE.

enumitems.name: NO
enumitems.comment: The network is not allowed to reroute the FRE.

enumitems.name: NOT_APPLICABLE
enumitems.comment: Rerouting considerations are not applicable.

enumitems.name: YES
enumitems.comment: The network is allowed to reroute the FRE.

classes.name: Route
classes.comment: This object class represents a partially ordered list of component FREs defining a route associated with an FRE.

fields.name: routeIdentifier
fields.comment: This attribute contains the unique identifier of the route within the referencing FRE.

fields.name: actualState
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the summary state of the component FREs associated to the Route.

fields.name: administrativeState
fields.comment: This attribute indicates whether the Route is currently administratively enabled to support the FRE ("unlocked") or not ("locked"). There is not any relationship with the actualState attribute of the Route. </br></br>The values can be interpreted as follows: </br>- "locked", the route is not allowed to be active </br>- "unlocked", the route is allowed to be active.

fields.name: additionalInformation
fields.comment: This attribute allows the communication from the target OS to the requesting OS of additional information which is not explicitly modelled.

fields.name: multiRoutePackage
fields.comment: Pulls in the package of attributes relevant to cases where there are multiple routes related to the FRE.

fields.name: isExclusive
fields.comment: This attribute indicates whether the component FREs of this Route can be shared in Routes of other FREs (False) or not (True). This applies regardless of other state considerations. If True then MultiRouteManagement should be included.</br></br>

fields.name: freRefList
fields.comment: Partially ordered list of FREs defining the Route.

classes.name: RoutingConstraintEffort
classes.comment: Indicates the degree to which the routing constraints should be met.

enumitems.name: BEST_EFFORT
enumitems.comment: The routing contraints are a preference but not meeting them is acceptable.

enumitems.name: EXACT_MATCH
enumitems.comment: The routing constraints must be met exactly.

classes.name: RoutingParameters
classes.comment: Package of routing parameters related to the fabric of the network exposed via TopologicalLink and NetworkForwardingDomain.

fields.name: sharedRiskGroupList
fields.comment: This attribute specifies the shared risk that in general is considered against the physical environment. It is defined as a sequence of {risk type, and sequence of shared risk references (strings)}.

classes.name: TerminationPointEncapsulation
classes.comment: The TerminationPointEncapsulation (TPE) represents one or more functions that terminate/originate a signal that adapt a signal for use, and that enable a signal to propagate. Hence a TPE can represent the end point of a signal flow. The TPE can also represent the intermediate point of a signal flow.A TPE is capable of encapsulating multiple transport functions (G.805 termination functions, adapters, points etc.) at many different layers where the encapsulated transport functions are all related to the same signal flow.  The encapsulated layers may be exposed via usage of instances of LayerTermination (LT).The TPE deals equivalently with unidirectional and bidirectional flows.

fields.name: tpeType
fields.comment: This attribute represents the name of the specification that describes the construction of the TPE emphasising for example the access to the TPE and whether it is associated with a physical port directly or not. Amongst other things this attribute would identify whether the TPE is a PTP, CTP or FTP.

fields.name: asapRefList
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the assignment of one or more Alarm Severity Assignment Profiles (ASAP) to the TPE.

fields.name: egressTmdRef
fields.comment: Pointer to a Tmd associated with the traffic leaving the TPE (i.e. egress).

fields.name: ingressTmdRef
fields.comment: Pointer to a Tmd associated with the traffic arriving at the TPE (i.e. ingress).

fields.name: protectedTpeRefList
fields.comment: Identifies one other TPE that is in a protection relationship with the TPE with this pointer.

fields.name: supportedTpeRefList
fields.comment: The list of TPEs supported by a specific equipment.

fields.name: tpeInOtherViewRefList
fields.comment: This attribute lists TPEs (in other name spaces) that represent at least some of the same resources in the network as the referencing TPE. For example this supports the navigation between a fully virtualized TPE and a TPE more closely bound to the physical equipment (such as the relationship between an SNP of the ASON Control Plane and a CTP of the physical network).

fields.name: attachedTpeRefList
fields.comment: Lists the TPEs that are attached to the PhysicalPort.

fields.name: encapsulatedLtList
fields.comment: Pulls in the list of LTs describing the termination of protocol layers encapsulated in the TPE.

fields.name: isEquipmentProtected
fields.comment: This attribute indicates whether or not the TPE is supported by a protected Equipment.

fields.name: egressTmdState
fields.comment: This attribute contains the state of consistency between a TPE and its associated egress TransmissionDescriptor.

fields.name: ingressTmdState
fields.comment: This attribute contains the state of consistency between a TPE and its associated ingress TransmissionDescriptor.

classes.name: TopologicalLink
classes.comment: The TopologicalLink_ represents a communication relationship between network entities and indicates that information is intended to flow between those network entities. The TopologicalLink_ always represents a logical relationship. Similar to Link [5] of 3GPP and TopologicalLink of SID/MTOSI [7]

fields.name: zEndTpeRefList
fields.comment: The value of this attribute shall be the Distinguished Name of the alphabetically first instance in the Link subclass name to which this link/relation is associated (i.e., pointing to the instance of <X> as described in the definition of Link IOC in the present document). </br>As an example, with Link_As_Slf, aEnd would contain the Distinguished Name of the AsFunction instance, and the zEnd would contain the Distinguished Name of SlfFunction instance.</br></br>A TL must have at least two ends. A TL may have no z ends.</br></br>Note that this attribute is likely to change.

fields.name: asapRef
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the assignment of an Alarm Severity Assignment Profiles (ASAP) to the TL.

classes.name: TrafficMappingTable
classes.comment: The TrafficMappingTable provides the rules for complex manipulation of components flows within the flow dealt with by the instance of LayerTermination. An example of an application is for Etherenet where a particular flow may require CTAG subflow manipulation.

fields.name: encapsulatedTmtrList
fields.comment: Pulls in the rows of the TrafficMappingTable.

classes.name: TrafficMappingTableRow
classes.comment: The TrafficMappingTableRow provides a specific rule for one manipulation, of a set of manipulations, of one or more components flows within the flow dealt with by the instance of LayerTermination.

fields.name: trafficConditioningProfileRef
fields.comment: Pointer to the TrafficConditioningProfile, an entity that defines a sequence of name value pairs that can be used to define various properties associated with the manipulation of the component flow identified and described in the TrafficMappingTableRow.

fields.name: vlanIdRange
fields.comment: This attribute states the VLAN ID or VLAN ID range to which the row applies.

fields.name: priority
fields.comment: This attribute states the traffic priority for the vlanRange to which this row applies.

fields.name: trafficClass
fields.comment: This attribute states the traffic class for the priority and vlanRange to which this row applies.

fields.name: trafficConditioningParameterList
fields.comment: This attribute represents a list of traffic conditioning parameters which can be set and/or retrieved at a specified connectionless layer on a Termination Point (TP) via this TMT as an alternative to use of a TCP or augmenting the TCP.

classes.name: MultiLayerSubNetwork
classes.comment: This object class is an abstraction of the topology provided by the target OS which describes the potential for SubNetwork Connections. Top-level Multi Layer Subnetworks are subnetworks contained directly under either the target OS or a Management Domain. See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0021 and R_TMF518_NRF_I_0021.

fields.name: type
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the type of the Subnetwork. </br>See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0023.

fields.name: supportedRateList
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the supported connection layer rates of the subnetwork.

fields.name: ituArcStateAndStatusList
fields.comment: See R_TMF518_NRB_I_0001 and R_TMF518_NRB_I_0004. </br>See supporting document SD1-8_encodingX731M3100...\..\Framework\SD\SD1-8_encodingX731M3100.pdf

classes.name: PhysicalTerminationPoint
classes.comment: This object class is an actual or potential end point of a Topological (physical) Link. The PTP does participate in associations unique to the PTP class (i.e., associations which do not apply to CTPs and therefore cannot be captured via the TP superclass). See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0007.

classes.name: Route
classes.comment: This object class represents a partially ordered list of Cross-Connects defining the route for a Subnetwork Connection. See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0035 and R_TMF518_NRF_I_0036.

fields.name: routeIdentifier
fields.comment: This attribute contains the unique identifier within the SNC name.

fields.name: crossConnectList
fields.comment: This attribute represents a route for a Subnetwork Connection. The Cross-Connects are listed from the NE on which the SNC starts (first entry) to the NE on which the SNC ends (last entry) and the aEnd(G)TpList and zEnd(G)TpList will name CTPs of the same or equivalent layer rate only.

fields.name: isIntendedRoute
fields.comment: This attribute defines the purpose of the route.

fields.name: actualState
fields.comment: This attribute defines the actual summary state of the Cross-Connects (CCs) associated to the Route.

fields.name: administrativeState
fields.comment: This attribute defines administratively the role that the Route shall play for the belonging SNC. There is not any relationship with the actualState attribute of the Route. </br>It can have the following values: </br>- "locked", the route is not allowed to be active </br>- "unlocked", the route is allowed to be active.

fields.name: isInUseBy
fields.comment: This attribute defines if at least one of the routes Cross-Connects or CTPs is carrying traffic of another SNC (True).

fields.name: isExclusive
fields.comment: This attribute defines that not any other routes of other SNCs can share any of the routes Cross Connects or CTPs, even in pending state (True).

fields.name: additionalInformation
fields.comment: This attribute allows the communication from the target OS to the requesting OS of additional information which is not explicitly modelled.

classes.name: SubNetworkConnection
classes.comment: This object class represents the relationship between Termination Points. All end point TPs related by an Subnetwork Connection (SNC) must support the same or an equivalent layer rate which is also the SNC's layer rate. In pending state, generic Connection Termination Point(s) of the SNC could be replied. Refer to the associated supporting document SD1-36_SNCTypes for explanation of SNC Properties, SNC Parameters, unidirectional SNCs, Point-to-Multipoint SNC, Routing Constraints and Route Discovery. See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0024 and R_TMF518_NRF_I_0025. For bundled SNCs see R_TMF518_NRF_I_0032.

fields.name: state
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the SNC connection state. </br>See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0028.

fields.name: direction
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the directionality of the SNC.

fields.name: layerRate
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the layer rate of the SNC. It is specified by the requesting OS upon object creation. </br> </br>Note: In case of a bundled SNC the value LR_Not_Applicable is used. The requesting OS can determine the layer rate by looking at the CTPs contained in the aEnd and zEnd GTPs.

fields.name: staticProtectionLevel
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the degree of internal resilience/protection of the SNC.

fields.name: type
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the external traffic flow through the SNC. </br>See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0029.

fields.name: aEndTpDataList
fields.comment: This attribute lists all A End TP names together with their TP data (TP Mapping Mode, Transmission Parameters).

fields.name: zEndTpDataList
fields.comment: This attribute lists all Z End TP names together with their TP data (TP Mapping Mode, Transmission Parameters).

fields.name: rerouteAllowed
fields.comment: This attribute specifies if the target OS/MEs are allowed and/or required to reroute this SNC if there is a failure on this SNC, periodically to optimize the routes, of for any other reason. It is an target OS/ME implementation whether this is done using network routing protocols or if the target OS/MEs detect the failure and take appropriate action to attempt to fix the SNC. </br>The NO value means that the target OS/MEs are not allowed to reroute the SNC. </br>The YES value means that the target OS/MEs are allowed to reroute the SNC and are required to attempt to reroute it upon failure. </br>The NA value is used when the requesting OS does not want to specify the exact target OS behaviour. In this case it is left up to the target OS to decide whether rerouting will be provided. It is also used if the target OS/MEs are allowed to reroute the SNC but not required to attempt to reroute it upon failure.

fields.name: networkRouted
fields.comment: This attribute specifies if the route for this SNC is computed by the network. </br>If rerouting is allowed, this attribute tells who last rerouted the SNC, the network (YES) or the EMS (NO).

fields.name: networkReroute
fields.comment: This attribute indicates if the reroute (if allowed) should be computed by the network (YES), by the EMS (NO), or if it does not matter (NOT_SET). </br>Changes in the value of this attribute lead to an AVC notification.

fields.name: revertive
fields.comment: This attribute defines if the SNC can be switched back to its original (intended) route. </br>In case the SNC is "revertive" (True), the restoration process will always switch to the intended route if possible, i.e. if there are no failures or if the intended route is not locked. </br>Changes in the value of this attribute lead to an AVC notification.

fields.name: isReportingAlarms
fields.comment: This attribute identifies whether alarm reporting for this subnetwork connection is administratively activated or de-activated. </br>Changes in the value of this attribute lead to an AVC notification. </br> </br>True = alarm reporting is activated; False = alarm reporting is de-activated.

fields.name: correlationIdentifier
fields.comment: This attribute contains information about relationships that this subnetwork connection may have to other objects. </br>Changes in the value of this attribute lead to an AVC notification.

fields.name: isBundledSnc
fields.comment: This attribute indicates if the SNC is a bundled SNC.

fields.name: mustRemoveGtps
fields.comment: This attribute defines that the target OS has to delete all the interior GTPs supporting the bundled SNC when the SNC is deleted. It is only used for bundled SNCs. </br> </br>It can take on two possible values: </br>- TRUE (the target OS must make a best-effort attempt to remove the interior GTPs that once belonged to the SNC) and </br>- FALSE (the requesting OS doesn't care if the target OS removes the interior GTPs or not). </br> </br>In the case that mustRemoveGTPs is set to "TRUE" and the target OS cannot remove all the interior GTPs, the target OS should return a list of the GTPs that could not be removed in the errorReason field of the deactivateAndDeleteSNC and deleteSNC operations. The errorReason will be "not all interior GTPs could be deleted" - this will be followed by the names of the GTPs that could not be deleted.

fields.name: isFixed
fields.comment: This attribute identifies if the SubnetworkConnection is fixed (i.e. cannot be deleted by the requestig OS). </br>A fixed SNC is defined a SNC whose all cross connects are fixed.

fields.name: mustRetainOldSnc
fields.comment: This attribute identifies if an original route of the SNC is maintained and that it is possible to swap back this route. </br>Changes in the value of this attribute lead to an AVC notification.

fields.name: priority
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the priority of the SNC. </br>Allowed values are = "0" , "1" , "2" , ... where zero (0) is the highest priority. </br>Changes in the value of this attribute lead to an AVC notification.

fields.name: aEndPointsRole
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the end point role of the aEndTPs of the SNC. </br>At a connection matrix (CM) end point the span of the SNC starts at a G.805 CP with a fixed or flexible connection through the ME at the SNC layer, i.e. the connectable layer of the end point. At a link connection (LC) end point connectivity is adapted from a server layer and the span of the SNC starts with a G.805 TCP. </br>See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0026.

fields.name: zEndPointsRole
fields.comment: This attribute indicates the end point role of the zEndTPs of the SNC. </br>At a connection matrix (CM) end point the span of the SNC starts at a G.805 CP with a fixed or flexible connection through the ME at the SNC layer, i.e. the connectable layer of the end point. At a link connection (LC) end point connectivity is adapted from a server layer and the span of the SNC starts with a G.805 TCP. </br>See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0026.

fields.name: routeGroupLabel
fields.comment: This attribute represents the Route Group the Subnetwork Connection is associated to. When a target OS creates a Call with diverse Route Groups, it assigns a Route Group label (which may be a number) to each SNC. SNCs in the same Route Group will be assigned the same value for routeGroupLabel. SNCs in different Route Groups will be assigned different values for routeGroupLabel.

fields.name: ituArcStateAndStatusList
fields.comment: See R_TMF518_NRB_I_0001 and R_TMF518_NRB_I_0004. </br>See supporting document SD1-8_encodingX731M3100...\..\Framework\SD\SD1-8_encodingX731M3100.pdf

classes.name: TerminationMode
classes.comment: The CTP can be mapped but currently is not (i.e., it does have contained potential CTPs, but currently has no contained actual CTPs). This indicates that the G.805 CP aggregated in the CTP is not connected to a TCP (that would be aggregated in the same CTP) and therefore the CTP is available for SNC/crossconnect connectivity (e.g. STS1 not terminated and not mapped to VT1.5i.e. not channelized).The FTP can be mapped on the server side but currently is not (i.e., it does have contained potential CTPs on the server side, but currently has no contained actual CTPs on the server side). This indicates that the FTP supports IM (Inverse Multiplexing) but the IM function is not active and the TCP within the FTP is available for external SNC/crossconnect connectivity.

enumitems.name: NEITHER_TERMINATED_NOR_AVAILABLE_FOR_MAPPING
enumitems.comment: The CTP can be mapped but currently is not (i.e., it does have contained potential CTPs, but currently has no contained actual CTPs). This indicates that the G.805 CP aggregated in the CTP is not connected to a TCP (that would be aggregated in the same CTP) and therefore the CTP is available for SNC/crossconnect connectivity (e.g. STS1 not terminated and not mapped to VT1.5i.e. not channelized).The FTP can be mapped on the server side but currently is not (i.e., it does have contained potential CTPs on the server side, but currently has no contained actual CTPs on the server side). This indicates that the FTP supports IM (Inverse Multiplexing) but the IM function is not active and the TCP within the FTP is available for external SNC/crossconnect connectivity.

enumitems.name: NOT_APPLICABLE
enumitems.comment: The CTP can not be mapped (i.e., it has no contained potential CTPs). This indicates that an SNC/crossconnect can be used to connect the G.805 TCP of the CTP to the connection point of another CTP/FTP. This only applies to CTPs that connect on their server side and are related to the containing PTP/FTP on their client side.The FTP can not be mapped on the server side (i.e., it has no contained potential CTPs on the server side). This indicates that an SNC/crossconnect can be used to connect the G.805 TCP of the FTP to the connection point of another CTP/FTP. This only applies to FTPs that connect on their server side and do not support IM (Inverse Multiplexing).

enumitems.name: TERMINATED_AND_AVAILABLE_FOR_MAPPING
enumitems.comment: The CTP can be mapped and currently is (i.e., it has contained actual CTPs). This indicates that the G.805 CPs adapted from the corresponding G.805 Termination Function within the CTP aggregate are available to provide client layer capacity (e.g. STS1 terminated and mapped to VT1.5 i.e. channelized). In this state the TCP will be sourcing and sinking traffic. This is only a valid value for CTPs that support client adaptation.The FTP can be mapped on the server side and currently is (i.e., it has contained actual CTPs on the server side). This indicates that the FTP supports IM (Inverse Multiplexing) and the server side contained CTPs (if any) are available for connection as the FTP is actively assembling the fragments of the IM. This value is not valid for an FTP that does not support IM. (see layering for more details).For ATM VP or VC CTP this value is used to model a VPC or a VCC terminating within the Managed Element (i.e. internal VP or VC Trails). Such a terminated ATM connection is used as a trail acting as a server for upper layer protocols (e.g., VCCs in case of a VPC TP,Frame Relay in case of a VCC TP). In the two switching layer ATM model, the VP layer acts as the infrastructure on which VC Connections (either PVC, SPVC or SVC) are routed and switched. This capability allows the operator to build a logical partitioning (VP overlay) of the physical ATM network by configuring VPCs (or VP "tunnels") which are terminated inside the subnetwork. Such overlay VP network allows operators to aggregate and segregate VCs according to their traffic management policy. In addition, the use of an intra-subnetwork VPC may provide for enhanced protection of the VC traffic by using 1+1 VP protection (VP protection is not supported in this release of the EMS-NMS interface). In order to be able to make routing decisions at VC level (e.g., explicit route constraint), the NMS needs to know the VP topology available from the ATM network.

classes.name: TerminationPointPool
classes.comment: This object class represents a set of Termination Points or Group Termination Points that are grouped. Properties that are common for all the TPs/GTPs in the TPPool are identified in the multiple associated commonTransmissionParameters. See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0014 and R_TMF518_NRF_I_0015.

fields.name: numberOfMembers
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the total number of TPs or GTPs currently contained in the TPPool.

fields.name: numberOfIdleMembers
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the number of currently contained idle TPs or GTPs in the TPPool.

fields.name: commonTransmissionParameterList
fields.comment: This attribute contains the common layers and Transmission Parameters associated with the TPs grouped by the associated TpPool (or contained by the GTPs that are grouped by the associated TPPool). </br>Refer to attached supporting document SD1-16_LayeredParameters for details of the currently defined Transmission Parameters.

fields.name: descriptionOfUse
fields.comment: This attribute contains a description of the specific use of the TPPool. </br>The description of use of an ATM VP TPPool would be "VirtualUNI", if all its VP CTPs are contained in the same real user network interface (UNI) (i.e., a tributary ATM NI CTP) that is partitioned into virtual UNIs (i.e., VP TPPools).

classes.name: TIPConnectionTerminationPoint
classes.comment: This object class is an actual or potential end point of a Subnetwork Connection or Flow Domain Fragment. For example, the ConnectionTerminationPoint (CTP) can represent a logical channel or a timeslot on a physical link. Note regarding naming: Wherever multiple layers are applicable to a particular CTP, the connectable layer is used as a basis for the name. When the CTP has no connectable layer, any layer that ensures name unicity can be used. See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0009 and R_TMF518_NRF_I_0010. For Flow Points in connectionless networks see R_TMF518_NRF_I_0018.

fields.name: connectionState
fields.comment: The values that this attribute may take are constrained by the value of the "direction" attribute of the CTP. There is also a dependency on the value of the "tpMappingMode" attribute of the CTP. </br>See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0037.

fields.name: tpMappingMode
fields.comment: Within the faÃ§ade definition, the CTP/FTP can act as an aggregate of associated G.805 TCPs, G.805 Termination Functions and G.805 CPs at one or more LayerRates. The CTP is contained within a PTP or FTP. The tpMappingMode attribute indicates and controls the connection of the named CP at a specified LayerRate to the dedicated G.805 TCP and associated G.805 Termination Function at the same LayerRate within the CTP/FTP.

classes.name: TIPTerminationPoint
classes.comment: This object class is the superclass of the CTP (ConnectionTerminationPoint) and PTP (PhysicalTerminationPoint) object classes. TP encapsulates object characteristics common to both CTPs and PTPs (i.e., common to end points (actual or potential) of Subnetwork Connections, Topological Links and Flow Domain Fragments). The layer rate of the TP is expressed in terms of the Transmission Parameters list attribute. See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0005 and R_TMF518_NRF_I_0006. For Connectionless Port Termination Points (CPTP) in connectionless network see R_TMF518_NRF_I_0016.

fields.name: direction
fields.comment: This attribute represents a static, inherent capability of the TP.

fields.name: tpProtectionAssociation
fields.comment: This attribute indicates whether the TP has an associated protection TP and, if so, what kind of protection association exists.

fields.name: isEdgePoint
fields.comment: This attribute indicates if the TP is an edge point of at least one Subnetwork or Flow Domain, i.e. if it is an end point of a potential inter-Subnetwork/inter-FlowDomain Topological Link. </br>See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0008.

fields.name: isEquipmentProtected
fields.comment: This attribute indicates whether or not the TP is supported by a protected Equipment.

fields.name: egressTmdState
fields.comment: This attribute contains the state of consistency between a TP and its associated egress TransmissionDescriptor.

fields.name: ingressTmdState
fields.comment: This attribute contains the state of consistency between a TP and its associated ingress TransmissionDescriptor.

fields.name: transmissionParameterList
fields.comment: This attribute contains the layered Transmission Parameters associated with the different layers that are encapsulated within the TP. </br>Refer to attached supporting document SD1-16_LayeredParameters for details of the currently defined Transmission Parameters...\..\Framework\SD\SD1-16_LayeredParameters.pdf

fields.name: ituArcStateAndStatusList
fields.comment: See R_TMF518_NRB_I_0001 and R_TMF518_NRB_I_0004. </br>See supporting document SD1-8_encodingX731M3100...\..\Framework\SD\SD1-8_encodingX731M3100.pdf

classes.name: TopologicalLink
classes.comment: This object class represents a physical link between two or more (usual case two; more than two e.g., for representing RPR transport connectivity) PTPs or a trail between two TPs. A Topological Link (TL) may traverse through DWDM equipment and optical transport networks managed by another target OS. The TL reported by the first target OS in that case could correspond to a (regenerator) section under its management domain. It is up to the requesting OS user to put together the exact topology of the network in such cases, based on the reported Managed Elements and TLs. For unidirectional TLs the aEndTP marks the traffic source whereas the zEndTP marks the traffic sink. See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0019 and R_TMF518_NRF_I_0020.

fields.name: direction
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the direction of the Topological Link.

fields.name: layerRate
fields.comment: This attribute identifies the layer and bandwidth (rate) of the Topological Link (TL). </br>The Layer Rate of a TL is determined by the lowest common Layer Rate of the end point TPs, about which the target OS has knowledge (with the physical layer being the very lowest).

fields.name: isReportingAlarms
fields.comment: This attribute provides an indication of whether alarm reporting for this Topological Link is administratively activated or de-activated. </br>True = alarm reporting is activated; False = alarm reporting is de-activated.

fields.name: ituArcStateAndStatusList
fields.comment: See R_TMF518_NRB_I_0001 and R_TMF518_NRB_I_0004. </br>See supporting document SD1-8_encodingX731M3100...\..\Framework\SD\SD1-8_encodingX731M3100.pdf

classes.name: TrafficConditioningProfile
classes.comment: This object class represents a collection of attributes, which are used to define the traffic conditioning parameters (e.g., bandwidth characteristics) on a Termination Point (TP). See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0052, R_TMF518_NRF_I_0053 and R_TMF518_NRF_I_0054.

fields.name: isDefaultProfile
fields.comment: This attribute defines the TC Profile as a non-deleteable profile.

fields.name: layeredTrafficConditioningParameterList
fields.comment: This attribute represents a list of traffic conditioning parameters which can be set and/or retrieved at a specified connectionless layer on a Termination Point (TP) having this TC Profile assigned. Refer to chapter "Traffic conditioning parameters" of the supporting document SD1-16_LayeredParameters for details of the currently defined traffic conditioning parameters...\..\Framework\SD\SD1-16_LayeredParameters.pdf

classes.name: TransmissionDescriptor
classes.comment: This object class is a collection of attributes which are used to define multi-layered transmission parameters and additional info parameters on a resource; e.g., a TP. See R_TMF518_NRF_I_0042 and R_TMF518_NRF_I_0043.

fields.name: transmissionParameterList
fields.comment: This attribute contains the layered Transmission Parameters associated with the different layers that are encapsulated within the Transmission Descriptor. </br>Refer to attached supporting document SD1-16_LayeredParameters for details of the currently defined Transmission Parameters...\..\Framework\SD\SD1-16_LayeredParameters.pdf

fields.name: additionalObjectInfoList
fields.comment: This attribute contains additional parameters which can be set and/or retrieved on an object having this Transmission Descriptor (TMD) assigned as (egress or ingress) TMD.

fields.name: externalRepresentationReference
fields.comment: This attribute provides a means to store at the target OS a reference to the external representation of the Transmission Descriptor.
